<div class='content-block'>
<h1>Omega: search for your website</h1>
<p>
If you're after a packaged search engine for your website, you should take a look at <a href='docs/omega/'>Omega</a>. Unlike most other website search solutions, Xapian's versatility allows you to extend Omega to meet your needs as they grow. If you need to, you can replace all parts of Omega one by one as your requirements change, and keep on using the same database you started with.
</p>

<p>
Omega operates on a set of databases. Each database is created and updated separately using either omindex or <a href='docs/omega/scriptindex'>scriptindex</a>. You can search these databases (or any other Xapian database with suitable contents) via a web front-end provided by <a href='docs/omega/cgiparams'>omega</a>, a CGI application. A search can also be done over more than one database at once.
</p>
</div>

<div class='content-block'>
<h1>Documentation</h1>

<p>There is lots of <a href='docs/'>documentation</a> available, from <a href='docs/quickstart'>how to get started with Xapian</a>, through <a href='docs/apidoc/html/annotated.html'>using the library</a>, to advanced topics such as <a href='docs/admin_notes'>system administration</a> and <a href='docs/scalability'>scaling</a>. There's also information about Xapian's internals, if you want to get involved in development, and of course details of how to use all the Xapian tools, including the <a href='docs/omega/'>Omega search engine</a>.</p>

